4. FAST JSON PARSING WITH simd-json
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

simd-json is 20-40% faster than serde_json on AVX2 hardware.
Key requirement: it needs a mutable byte slice (it modifies the buffer in-place).

use simd_json::BorrowedValue;

fn parse_ws_message(buf: &mut Vec<u8>, raw: &[u8]) -> Option<MarketEvent> {
    buf.clear();
    buf.extend_from_slice(raw);

    // simd_json::to_borrowed_value operates in-place on the buffer
    match simd_json::to_borrowed_value(buf.as_mut_slice()) {
        Ok(BorrowedValue::Object(obj)) => {
            let event_type = obj.get("event_type")?.as_str()?;
            match event_type {
                "book"  => parse_book_delta(&obj),
                "order" => parse_order_event(&obj),
                _       => None,
            }
        }
        _ => None,
    }
}

Profile your actual workload — if messages are small (<1KB), standard serde_json
may be fast enough and easier to work with. Benchmark both.

